12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics 411
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Definition - Statistics statistics as a scientific method of collection of theories and techniques of summarising numerical information to make sense out of it. Numerical information or data are numbers with a context as statistics in brief, is the science of data and the art of examining them.
Studying statistics can help us feel much comfortable while handling and interpreting a set of figures and numbers.

Engineers often study data on quality and reliability of the manufactured products.
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Data is defined as known or assumed facts and figures from which conclusion can be drawn. 
Data are used to make decisions
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: to support decisions already made, to provide reasons behind happening of certain events and to make predictions of events to come. Some kind of analysis is required to convert data into information.
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics means 'numerical description' of facts and in common usage. The term statistics has dual meaning. Statistics in plural sense means data, i.e. the numerical information arising out of the events in connection with any sphere of human experience when a host of uncontrolled causes are acting together. 

On the other hand, statistics in singular sense, refers to the field or discipline of study. It deals with a methods of analysis of data. In this sense, statistics is defined as the scientific methods required for collections classifying, summarising, analysing and interpreting numerical information.
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Recently, a new definition of statistics has evolved. This definition defines statistics not as a body of methods, nor as a collection of data.
12/14/21, 11:44 - Sarkar Msc Bda: , but has an activity. It says that statistics is to increase our understanding to promote human welfare and to improve our quality of life and well-being by advancing the discovery and effective use of knowledge from data. The data with all their uncertainty, variability.

12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Regarding the methodology used in analysis of data two broad mass of statistics can be identified. Those two branches of statistics are are descriptive statistics and inferential statistics.
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Descriptive statistics provides the numerical and graphical method to look for the patterns in the dataset. It deals with the collection, organisation, summarisation.
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: and presentation of data in a convenient form.
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Inferential statistics discusses the ways of making prediction or drawing conclusion about population characteristics based on the data collected.
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Scope of statistics : In India, study of statistics as a scientific discipline and it's application was introduced by Prof. Prashanta Chandra Mohalanovis in early 1920s.
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: He came in contact with two outstanding statistician - Karl Pearson and R. A. Fizher. He Become interested their work and implied to do research on the works. He formed a group of scientists to work together on the development of stats.later In 1931 he founded Indian Statistical Institute for the study and research in statistics, initially housed at Physics Department, Presidency College, Kolkata.

In 1951 it was shifted to its present place(BT Road, Dakshineswar, Kolkata).
12/15/21, 11:28 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Misuses of Statistics:

There are some sayings like: 

"There are three kind of Lies -
Lies, Damn Lies and Statistics"

"An ounce of truth will produce tons of Statistics. "

Real figures and numbers cannot lie. Wrong Pictures may come out due to fallible data or interpretation. Statistics is rather useful in extracting and establishing the truth behind the data but it must be used in proper perspective.

12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Classification of collection of data

Any set of data contains some information about certain group of individuals. Thse individuals are called units. 

The entire group of individuals that we want info about is called population. A part of the population which we actually study in order to gather information is called sample.

The complete list of individuals or units in the population is called sampling frame. The sampling frame is very essential for the purpose of drawing the sample from the population. While studying a population we focus on one or more characteristics of the units in the
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: population. For e.g., we may be interested in characteristics, like age, gender blood group
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: , monthly phone bills etc.
These are known as variable(s).
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The name "variable" is derived from the fact "that the characteristics under study".
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: ..study may vary from individual to another."
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Measurement is the process of assigning values to the variables.
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: These values corresponding to an individuals are called observations
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: A single data value is obtained when a variable is actually measured on an unit. 

A collection of measurements or observations on one or more variables is called a dataset.
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: A data consisting observations on single variable is known as a "univariant data set"
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: and two (or more) variables is known as "bivariate" or "multivariate".
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: "univariate", not "univariant" (sorry)
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: When data are collected, the observations obtained from each unit of a population or a sample are recorded in the sequence they become available. 

The sequence of data before they are processed are called "raw data". When data are collected for every unit of a population it is called "census or complete enumeration", sampling otherwise.
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Clasification of data depends on the type of variable we measure.

We can observe different types of variables in practice each of which belongs to any category of the following broad classification - 

Variable -
| - qualitative / categorical
| - quantitative / numerical
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Qualitative -
| - ordinal
| - non-ordinal

Quantitative -
| - Discrete
| - Continuous

The variable which cannot be measured nuerically but can be measured by their quality is called "qualitative variable". Since these variables place individuals in different categories they are also called "categorical variables or attributes"
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: There are some categorical variables where the categories can be arranged in natural order, i.e. from Small to Big or from High to Low etc. Those variables are called "Ordinal Categorical" variables. For e.g. Income Group may be classified as High, Medium and Low etc.
12/20/21, 11:35 - Sarkar Msc Bda: In Other type of categorical variable , no idea of order among the categories exists. They are called "Non-Ordinal". For e.g. Blood Group, Religion, Marital Status etc. 

A variable which can be measured numerically is called "Quantitative / Numerical" variable. E.g. - Height, Weight, House Rent etc.

12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: stats
12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: A quantitative variable can further be classified as "discreet" and "continuous". 
A quantitative variable which can assume finite or countable nuber of discrete or isolaated values is called a discreet variable. For example, word length, family size, number of children in a family, number of telephone calls recieved by an operator each day etc.
12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: A quantitative variable which can assume any numerical value within a certain interval of real line is called a cont. variable. 
Daily temperature, time taken to finish a job, weight, height, age etc. are examples of continuous variable.
A cont. variable can assume values with finite or infinite range. 
From now on, by the word variable we will refer to a quantitative variable and by attribute we refer to qualitative variable.
12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Now, depending on the type of variable, we classify the data as follows -
12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: <Media omitted>
12/21/21, 11:17 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The data collected are called "Qualitative" if measured on a qualitative variable and quantitative if measured on a quantitative variable.  The quantitative data are measured on a naturally occuring numerical scale. The qualitative data do not contain any numerical observations.
The following is another way of classifying the data -

Data - 
* frequency data
* non-freq data

Non-freq data -
* Time series data
* cross sectional data

12/22/21, 11:32 - Aman Msc Bda: I think Degree of the polynomial
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Data where the values of the variable occur repeatedly and are expressed as the statement of possible variate values together with respective frequencies the number of times of occurence of that particular value in the dataset are called frequency data
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Data arranged or recorded in the form of series are called non-frequency data / series data. 
Non-frequency data are of two types - 1) Time Series data, and 2) Cross sectional data.
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The data collected on the same unit for the same variable for different points or periods of time are called "Time Series data"
Average Prices of houses of Calcutta for the years 1990 - 2002, Export of tea in last 12 months are the examples of Time Series data.
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Such data arise due to the change in variable values over time
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The data collected on different units for the same point or periods of time are called "Cross Sectional data". The present prices of same cars of different make is an example of Cross Sectional data. 

In particular, if cross sectional data relate to different  places, then it is called Spital (or Geographical) Series data, such as maximum temperature of different cities in India on a particular day, total population of different states as per 2011 census.
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The data that are measured across two dimensions, time and cross section are called Panel data. For example, the data on petroleum prices for last seven years in five cities  in India
12/22/21, 11:34 - Sarkar Msc Bda: -- Collection Of Data --

Every statistical investigation begins with a definite objective and collection of data is the first step towards achieving this objective. At the time of collecting data, we have to keep the following basic points in mind what purpose the data are expected to serve, what the related variables are and what the target population, i.e. what individuals the data are going to describe. 
There are two sources of data, 1) Primary source and 2) Secondary source. Primary source is a source where data collected directly from the field of enqquiry and Secondary source where data originally collected by someone are available in a published form.

1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: ----------Stats 25th Jan-------
1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: ```Relative Frequency```
1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Relative Frequency of a variate value (or class of values) is the proportion of observations corresponding to that particular value (or class). It is obtained by dividing the respective frequency by the total frequency and is given by:

 Relative frequency of a variate value = Frequency of that value / total frequency

It lies between 0 and 1. The relative frequencies of all values in a dataset adds upto 1. It gives the relative importance of a variate value in relation to the total frequency and thus makes two or more similar types of datasets comparable.
Sometimes, the relative frequencies are expressed in percentage as (frequency / total frequency * 100), i.e., (relative frequency * 100) which is known as percent frequency. Expressed as percents, the present frequency of all values should add up to 100. Sometimes, this total may deviate little from 100 because of the error due to rounding off the values.
1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: ```Frequency Distribution of a Discrete Variable```
1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Here we discuss how to construct a frequency distribution of a discrete variable from a raw dataset. In this connection we will also define the cumulative frequency -- Less than type & More than type. We use Tally marks for the purpose of counting the frequencies conveniently, for each value of the variable. First we list all possible values of the variable in ascending order. Then we put a tally against each value of the variable in the dataset. Each tally represents one frequency. We read off each observation in the raw dataset and for each one we put a tally againtst the corresponding variate value in the frequency table and finally we count the tally marks for each variate value. This helps us counting the frequencies for each value of the variable and minimizes the chance of making errors in counting the frequencies from raw data.
1/25/22, 11:29 - Sarkar Msc Bda: We make a group of five tallies (/////) in order to avoid error in counting a large number of tallies.

Cumulative Frequency of 'Less than type' corresponding to each variate value is obtained by cumulating or adding frequencies successively from the top of the frequency distribution upto the frequency of that value. i.e. Adding its frequency to the frequency of all the values of the variable smaller than that. 

Similarly, the cumulative frequency of 'More than type' for each variate value is obtained by adding it's frequency to the frequencies of all variate values higher than that. Thus we can obtain cumulative freuencies of 'Less than type' ('More than type') by adding frequencies successively starting from the top(bottom) of the frequency table.

Central Universities such as Central University of Haryana, Central university of South Bihar etc, have opened their gates for students to take offline classes. Also in the Latest Guidelines Government has specified that they will be reopening schools for 6th to 9th classes by 10th February 2022. We think its high time and the administration of our university should focus on calling us to the campus.

We have been sitting in our homes forÂ the last 2 years because of covid and The Online classes are really tiring. We students are fully vaccinated and are ready to join the university campus Offline. We would really appreciate if you permit us to join the campus.

Thank You

2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Stem and leaf plot

A stem plot gives a quick idea about the shape of the distribution. We can also have te idea about the centre and spread of the distribution from a stemplot. It works best for a small set of observations. It uses actual value of the dataset.
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: A stemplot portrays the shape of the distribution, data clusters, outliers(if any) in a very convenient and effective way. In the same plot, a number in a vertical column on the left of the display are stem values and each number to the right of the vertical line is a leaf, which corresponds to each of the observations in the data. Now we discuss about teh construction of a stem plot in brief for a value in a same dataset -
1. One or more leading digits for the stem values. The trailing digit becomes the leaf
2. List possible stem values in a vertical col.
3. Record the leaf(last digit should be the leaf) for every observation beside the corresponding same value.
4. Arrange them in an increasing order.
5. Indicate the unit for the stem and leaves at some place in the display
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The following example illustrates how to construct a stem plot (example) - 
Here ae the runs scored by a cricket player in the same 15 cricket matches she played - 
54,
59,
35,
41,
46,
25,
47,
60,
54,
46, 
49,
46, 
41,
34,
32.
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Stem                  Leaf
--------------------------
2                         2  5
3                         4  5
4                         1  1 6 6 6 7 9
5                         4 4 9
6                          0

N.B. The last reading/score is 22 instead of 32
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Basically, Stem: Tens digit
Leaf: Ones Digit
2/8/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Graphical Representation of the Discreet Distribution

1. Column Diagram
2. Frequency Diagram

2/14/22, 11:13 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics
2/14/22, 11:13 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Our basic objective with a data set is to summarize the data to make sense out of it. Towards this objective, firstly, we try to give a genral impression about the data throughtout the use of tables and different diagrams. These tools provides a summary picture of the data. 
The visual comparison of the data is subjective in the sense that different people may draw different conclusions about the extent of similarity or dissimilarity.
Therefore it's desirable to assign  concrete numercal measures to specific aspects of the distribution or the data, so that a comparison is not based solely on subjective assessment.

Secondly, our objective is to provide some numerical measureswhich will d escribe the main features of the data which is given below -
1. Measure of Central Tendency
2. Dispersion
3. Skewness
4. Kurtosis
2/14/22, 11:13 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Explanations

1. Central Tendency of a data set is the tendency of the data, to cluster or to centre about some typical value. This value, a central value which is used to represent the entire data set is known as a measure of central tendency. 
A good measure of central tendency should possess the following characteristics - 
i. It should be rigidly defined so that nobody should have any discretion for choosing it's value
ii. It should simple to understand and easy to calculate.
iii. It should be based on all observations.
iv. It should be least affected by sampling fluctuation. It should not vary much from sample to sample
v. It should be capable for further algebraic treatment.
vi. It should not be affected much by the presence of extreme values.

Now we will discuss the following measures of central tendency -
i. Arithmetic mean
ii. Geometric mean
iii. Harmonic mean
iv. Median
v. Mode
vi. Quartile
vii. Percentile

Most widely used measures of central tendency are Arithmetic mean or simple Mean, Median and Mode. Geometric mean and Harmonic mean are two other measures of Central Tendency which maybe useful in some particular situations under certain condition(s). All of the three quartiles (or 99% percentile) are not a measure of Central Tendency if taken indivdually. Only second Quartile and 50th percentile is Quartiles are used in measuring Dispersion and Skewness.
2/14/22, 11:13 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Arithmetic Mean - The AM is most commonly encountered and best understood of the measures of central tendency. It is popularly referred to as "average". It is considered as most important measure of central tendency as it satisfies some important mathematical properties. It works as a Centre Of Gravity of whole distribution. Balancing the values on either side of it.

2/14/22, 11:21 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics
2/14/22, 11:21 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Our basic objective with a data set is to summarize the data to make sense out of it. Towards this objective, firstly, we try to give a genral impression about the data throughtout the use of tables and different diagrams. These tools provides a summary picture of the data. 
The visual comparison of the data is subjective in the sense that different people may draw different conclusions about the extent of similarity or dissimilarity.
Therefore it's desirable to assign  concrete numercal measures to specific aspects of the distribution or the data, so that a comparison is not based solely on subjective assessment.

Secondly, our objective is to provide some numerical measureswhich will d escribe the main features of the data which is given below -
1. Measure of Central Tendency
2. Dispersion
3. Skewness
4. Kurtosis
2/14/22, 11:21 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Explanations

1. Central Tendency of a data set is the tendency of the data, to cluster or to centre about some typical value. This value, a central value which is used to represent the entire data set is known as a measure of central tendency. 
A good measure of central tendency should possess the following characteristics - 
i. It should be rigidly defined so that nobody should have any discretion for choosing it's value
ii. It should simple to understand and easy to calculate.
iii. It should be based on all observations.
iv. It should be least affected by sampling fluctuation. It should not vary much from sample to sample
v. It should be capable for further algebraic treatment.
vi. It should not be affected much by the presence of extreme values.

Now we will discuss the following measures of central tendency -
i. Arithmetic mean
ii. Geometric mean
iii. Harmonic mean
iv. Median
v. Mode
vi. Quartile
vii. Percentile

Most widely used measures of central tendency are Arithmetic mean or simple Mean, Median and Mode. Geometric mean and Harmonic mean are two other measures of Central Tendency which maybe useful in some particular situations under certain condition(s). All of the three quartiles (or 99% percentile) are not a measure of Central Tendency if taken indivdually. Only second Quartile and 50th percentile is Quartiles are used in measuring Dispersion and Skewness.
2/14/22, 11:21 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Arithmetic Mean - The AM is most commonly encountered and best understood of the measures of central tendency. It is popularly referred to as "average". It is considered as most important measure of central tendency as it satisfies some important mathematical properties. It works as a Centre Of Gravity of whole distribution. Balancing the values on either side of it.

2/15/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Statistics
2/15/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: AM for ungrouped data:

The AM of a dataset is the sum of the observed values divided byt he total number of observations in the dataset. The AM of a series of n observations x1, x2, .., xn is given by 

x-bar = (x1 + x2 + .. xn)/n 

Example : The number of children of 5 families are 3,2,1,4,2. Find the average number of children/family.

soln: x-bar = 1/5(3+2+1+4+2) = 24
2/15/22, 11:16 - Sarkar Msc Bda: AM for grouped data: If x1,x2, ... xk be the k values of a variable nd f1,f2,.., fn be the respective frequencies or weight, then AM = x-bar =

4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Stats april 27
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Analysis of categorical data and Association of Independence
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The analysis of association is relevant whenever a study encompasses two or more variables. Here, we will discuss the method of detecting and describing association between two qualitative or categorical variables. Here we considered both of the main types of categorical variables : nominal and ordinal. 
For the sake of simplicity, we mostly consider that both the variables have two or three categories. Results can be generalized for more categories without putting much effort. There is said to be an association between two variables if the value of one variable changes as the value of the other changes. Most bivariate analysis identify one variable as response variable and other variable as an explanatory variable. 
At the outset we must take it clear that the bivariate statistical tools discussed earlier measuring associations between two quantitative variables can also be used for qualitative variables by suitably converting the categories into numerical method for analysing qualitative variables have been discussed independently for independent interest. The methods introduced here will help us is the questions like -
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: 1. Is there any Association between job satisfaction and income ?
2. Is colour blindness more common among males and females?
3. Is there any regional variation in smoking habit of people?
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Here we will introduce some statistical tools which will tell us about the existence of association between two categorical variables and then we will give a few simple measures of association to determine the strength of association between the variables. By analysing the strength of association we can determine whether the association is strong and important for practical purposes. It is worthwhile mention that most of the critical measures of association for categorical variables are beyond this scope of present discussion.
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: We must remember that the lack of association of variables will imply independence. By measures of association, we mean a statistic, a function of sample observation which summarises the strength of statistical dependency between two variables.
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: || Contingency Table ||

The data for analysis of two categorical variables are classified in two way tables known as contingency table. This style of table displays the number of subjects or individuals observed at all combinations of possible categories for the two variables. 

Construction of a contingency table is the first step in studying association in two categorical variables. Both the variables have two categories, the two-way table representing the data is known as 2X2 Contingency Table. The classification where variable are classified into more than two classes , say r X s, known as manifold classification and the corresponding two way table is known as r X s contingency table. 

In a Contingency Table, the Row Totals gives the marginal distribution of Row Variables and the Column totals gives the marginal distribution of the column variables. 
The table itself gives the joint distribution  of  two variables. 
Two categorical variables are statistically independent if the percentage of the values in any particular category of one variable is same across all categories of the other variables.
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: The way we expressed the concept of independence is actually based on the conditional distribution of one variable within the categories of other Variables.
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: We say that two variables are statistically independent if the population cond. dist. of one variable are identical at each category of other variables. The variables are statistically dependent if the cond. dist. are not identical.
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Example : A following data have been obtained from a survey on "Do men and women differ in their selection of the faculties in their study in a college?"
4/27/22, 11:25 - Sarkar Msc Bda: Example : A following data have been obtained from a survey on "Do men and women differ in their selection of the faculties in their study in a college?"
Examine how faculty selection depends on gender for that college.

7/6/22, 11:14 - Deepti Kiran Msc Bda: Dear Ma'am,/Sir,

Greetings!



As per the recruitment drive of Argusoft India Ltd. the process will start from tomorrow(7th July 2022).


Please find below the schedule of the placement drive to be held virtually. 

7th July 2022, 10:00am- Pre-Placement Talk (30-40 minutes)
7th July 2022, 11:00am- Online Test, Followed by online interview of qualified students
8th July 2022- Continued online interviews of qualified students 
8th July 2022- Online interviews of qualified students, in case any are still left

For the instructions for the online test process, please refer below:
Instructions - 

1. The test will comprise of three sections -

     -Verbal reasoning

     -Non-verbal reasoning

     -Reading comprehension

2. The test will be of 60 minutes. 

3. It is mandatory for each candidate to score more than 60% in each section to clear the test. 

4. The test shall be conducted online. Webcam and mic are REQUIRED to be enabled during the test. 



Kindly share the above information with registered students to be prepared and present in the process on time. All students have to be in proper formal attire throughout the process.

Also sharing with you the list of students for your kind reference.





Thanks & Regards,


Rony Sharma
Training & Placement Officer
Central University of Rajasthan

On Thu, Jun 30, 2022 at 1:18 PM Central University of Rajasthan_Placement Cell <placements@curaj.ac.in> wrote:
Dear Ma'am,/Sir,

Greetings!


Argusoft India Ltd. is willing to hire students from Central University of Rajasthan for the profile of Programmer Analyst.



Sharing with you the details of the company and job description as below:


About Argusoft:

Argusoft India Ltd. is a software solution design company. Argusoft's 'American style, entrepreneurial' work culture emphasizes work-life balance, and hence, our culture is often described as a  good mix of work and play by our current and past Argonauts! Our annual team-building exercises are something that all our fellow Argonauts look forward to! 


Aiming at the holistic development of our fellow employees because we believe that if they grow, Argusoft grows! We provide continuous training, a large peer resource pool, creative development, and a motivating and challenging environment, changing the way you look at a job environment. 


Argusoft supports talent to take risks, explore new avenues and ultimately achieve personal and professional excellence. We encourage family-oriented activities and corporate social responsibility, inculcating a sense of giving amongst our Argonauts.


Awards & Recognizations:

Great Place to Work for 2022-2023

Gujarat IT Leadership Award 2018- Most Admired IT Company of the year.

Best ICT Initiative in Public Sector Gujarat 

Recognized by NetApp for the technology innovation that has made a social impact. 

ISO/IEC 27001:2013 Certified Company

ISO 14001:2015 Certified Company

ISO 9001:2015 Certified Company

ISO/IEC 20000-1:2018 Certified Company

ICT Award for AI Based Dynamic Business Automation


To know more visit website: www.argusoft.com

LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/showcase/life-argusoft/

LinkedIn: https://www.linkedin.com/company/argusoft


Argusoft is willing to explore our institution for talent acquisition as they search for individuals with a fresh outlook and new ideas!

Please find the placement details mentioned below!


Job Description: 

Type of Industry: IT-Software Services

Position: Programmer Analyst

Job Type: Full Time- (Hybrid) Work From Home/ Work From Anywhere.



Probation:  Duration 06 months (Mandatory Work from Office) During the probation period from July 2023 to December 2023 candidates will have to work from the office. Post completion of the probation period candidate is free to Work from Anywhere/Work From Home.



Qualification: BE /BTech (Computer Science & Information Technology only), ME/MTech, MSc (IT/Computer).



Eligibility: Minimum aggregate marks of 60% and above in the first attempt in all academic courses, standard 10th onwards. Aggregate CGPA/ Percentage 6CGPA / 60% and above required for Semesters Exams. No Backlog.


On-Campus Recruitment Procedure of Argusoft: 


Stage 1. Pre-placement Talk 

Stage 2. Online Aptitude Technical /Communication Skill Test (MCQ & Descriptive)

Stage 3. Personal Interview ( 2-3 rounds)


Last Semester Project (No Obligation)

Project Training

6 Months (Optional)

Duration

January -June 2023



Package

INR 6.50- 7.50 Lac Per Year

Probation

6 Month (July-December 2023)

Stipend During Probation

INR 21000 Per Month



Request you to kindly share the data of interested students in the attached format by 1st June 2022.

Thanks & Regards,


Rony Sharma
Training & Placement Officer
Central University of Rajasthan
Email: placements@curaj.ac.in
Contact: 7014889031
